\section{Introduction}

Climate change is one of the most significant challenges facing humanity today \cite{caldeira2003anthropogenic}. It is increasingly recognized that the transition to a low-carbon economy is essential to limit global warming, thereby mitigating the impact of climate change \cite{campiglio2016beyond}. This transition will require significant changes in the way we produce and consume energy, and will have far-reaching economic implications.

\vspace{0.1cm}

Greenhouse gases (GHGs) emitted by economic activities are the primary cause for the abnormal increase in global temperatures, and their reduction are more so a major indicator of the transition towards a sustainable economy and a tool to lead the politics of change. International agreements like the Paris Agreement set GHG emission targets for the international community. For example, countries set Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) to meet the goal of limiting global warming to below 2Â°C by 2100. %NDCs can be adjusted to achieve carbon neutrality as quickly as possible. 
Notably, around two-thirds of the NDCs incorporate the implementation of a carbon price mechanism. The primary goal of this pricing strategy is to hold emitters responsible for the externalities induced by greenhouse gases (also known as the \textit{social cost of carbon} \cite{tol2011social}). The concept of carbon pricing pre-dates the Paris Agreement, as demonstrated by the introduction of an emission trading scheme (ETS) within the European Union (EU) in 2005 \cite{ellerman2008european}. In this scheme, carbon is assigned a market value, determined by the exchanges between companies operating in highly emitting sectors. In the EU, price is based on a quantity allocated by the Member States through a national allocation plan \cite{zetterberg2004analysis}. The quantity of allowances available to the market decreases each year, % (for instance, France reduces it by 1.74\% annually during the period 2013-20), 
with the ultimate goal of eliminating allowances entirely. Besides the EU-ETS, national or sub-national systems are already operating or under development in Canada, China, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Switzerland and the United States \cite{nachtigall2021economic}. This circumstance, along with increasingly stringent regulations, has resulted in a significant increase in carbon pricing. Based on projections aimed at limiting the temperature rise to below 2Â°C by 2100, carbon prices are expected to continue to rise, reaching levels that will be highly penalizing for carbon-intensive industries \cite{ngfs2021scenarios}. In addition, higher carbon prices can lead to global inflation, first in the fossil fuel supply chain and then in the entire price-production value chain \cite{moessner2022effects}. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

The impact of carbon regulations on businesses has naturally raised concerns about their ability to cope with the escalating costs of transitioning to a low-carbon economy, particularly in the face of an inflationary carbon market. As transition costs (such as carbon pricing) rise, we can see two plausible effects. First, the revenues of emitting firms are likely to decline, leading to a decline in their creditworthiness. Second, given the interdependence between industries and depending on the pricing power of sectors, even low-emitting sectors who rely on carbon-intensive industries may be affected by increased carbon pricing, with inflation transmitted along the value chain network.


\vspace{0.1cm}

Banks, which finance many potentially affected industries, are likewise exposed to climate transition risk born by companies, as increases in the carbon price can affect their credit exposure and capital values. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision recently created a Task Force on Climate-Related Financial Risks to address this new macro-financial risk, and to enhance financial stability. Its research has, for example, mapped climate-related financial risks \cite{basel2021drivers}, surveyed Basel Committee members to learn about their various initiatives on this subject \cite{basel2020climate}, or identified their associated methodologies \cite{basel2021climate}. To manage climate transition risk, banks will need to take a range of steps \cite{brunnermeier2020central}, including: developing climate risk strategies 
%(to identify, measure, and manage climate transition risk)
, conducting stress tests 
%(to understand the potential impact of different climate scenarios on their portfolios)
, engaging with clients 
%(to encourage them to transition to more sustainable business models)
, investing in sustainability 
%(including reducing their own carbon footprint and promoting sustainable business practices) 
and collaborating with stakeholders. 
%(banks should collaborate with regulators, policymakers, and other stakeholders to promote a coordinated approach to addressing climate transition risk). 

\vspace{0.1cm}

In this context, regulators have required banks and insurance companies to perform climate stress tests (CST) to evaluate their resilience to climate-related risks of their portfolios, and identify potential vulnerabilities (see the timeline in Figure \ref{fig:timeline}). 
Climate stress tests are designed to evaluate the resilience of financial institutions to climate-related risks and to identify potential vulnerabilities. An overview of the principle of a climate stress test for the global financial system is for example given in \cite{monasterolo2020climate}. Regulatory stress tests are based on the projection of macro-financial variables, based on a narrative. For the CST organized by the European Central Bank (ECB) in 2022 \cite{ecb2021climate}, the regulator used the scenarios and macro-financial trajectories of the Network for Greening the Financial System (NGFS) \cite{ngfs2021scenarios}, based on climate transition narratives proposed by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). In these scenarios, the evolution of macro-financial variables is directly linked to the increase in carbon and fossil fuel prices, showing an environment of high and increasing transition costs. In particular, regulators split the effects of transition costs into \textit{indirect effects} throughout macro-financial variables trajectories, and \textit{direct effects} when the cost is paid directly by companies. We find in the ECB's CST methodological document \cite{ecb2021climate} that:

\vspace{0.1cm}

\textit{``For the projections of the credit risk parameters, banks are asked to consider both (i) the direct impact of the shock on their counterparties (e.g. rising costs due to the increasing carbon price), and (ii) the impact from the changes in the macro variables that accompany the carbon price shock (e.g. lower aggregate demand), which are given as part of the scenario"}

