\vspace{0.1cm}

Banks already manage forward-looking macro-financial risks to meet regulatory stress testing exercises \cite{eba2021stress}, and are thus already prepared to incorporate the indirect effect into their forward-looking credit risk management. However, the direct effect of sector-dependent incremental costs requires new methodologies. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

In our paper, we focus on corporate exposure of banks. We propose a model to estimate the sensitivity of corporate rating transition matrices (TMs) related to a change in the carbon price paid. TMs are key measures for credit risk management in banks and are used to assess the regulatory capital of banks as defined in the Basel Accord \cite{basel2011global}. To do so, we combine a Leontief input-output model to diffuse the cost of carbon across the value chain of the economy and a model to represent TMs with low-dimensional factors. We obtain a new end-to-end model to generate stressed TMs from carbon price trajectories projected by the NGFS for several climate transition scenarios. We adjust the effect of carbon with a coefficient computed from the trajectories of carbon intensity, which depends on the scenario. As an illustration, we run the NGFS carbon price trajectories through our model to assess the sensitivity of US TMs to the direct transition price of carbon. We note that our model can be generalized to any additional cost associated with climate change mitigation, such as energy prices. % To the best of our knowledge, our end-to-end assessment model of TMs' sensitivity to carbon price (and more generally to any direct transition cost) with value chain effect is the first of its kind. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

Our paper is structured as follows. Section \ref{sec:definitions} presents important definitions. Section \ref{sec:key_elements} details the different elements from which we build our end-to-end approach, which relates additional costs to the geo-sectoral TMs of banks exposure. Related work is presented in Section \ref{sec:related_work}. Finally, we illustrate our approach on US transition matrices in Section \ref{sec:experiments} using the data presented in Section \ref{sec:data}. 

\section{Important definitions}
\label{sec:definitions}

\noindent \textbf{Greenhouse gas emissions (GHGs)} are the emissions of gases that contribute to the greenhouse effect and climate change as a result of human economic activities. %These gases include carbon dioxide (CO2), methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and fluorinated gases, such as hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) and sulfur hexafluoride (SF6).
GHG emissions related to economic activities arise from a wide range of sources, including the burning of fossil fuels for energy production, transportation, and industrial processes, as well as from agricultural activities, deforestation, and waste management. The quantity of GHG emitted by economic activities will depend on the industrial sector. A climate feature of sectors is the \textit{GHG intensity}, which is the quantity of GHG emitted divided by the production (e.g., the monetary value-added) generated by the activity. GHG emissions are categorized into three scopes: 1) direct emissions from production activities, 2) indirect emissions from imported electricity, heat or steam, and 3) all other indirect emissions. The majority of emissions fall under scope 3. We note that the scopes 2 and 3 of the production at a certain moment and location are the scope 1 of the production at another moment and/or location. The diffusion of the scope 1 emissions across the value chain transforms it into scopes 2 and 3. Hence, knowing the value chain of the economy enables us to compute the scopes 2 and 3 from scope 1 taking into account the dependencies between production activities \cite{meng2018tracing}.

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{Carbon pricing} is an instrument that aims to address the negative externalities of GHG emissions (known as \textit{social carbon cost} \cite{change2014synthesis}). GHG emitters must decide whether to pay a carbon price or to reduce their emissions. The \textit{Emissions Trading Scheme} (ETS) is a cap-and-trade system that establishes a market price for carbon. A \textit{voluntary offset mechanism} enables companies or states to reduce their emissions by financing a carbon reduction or sequestration project. The \textit{internal carbon price} is a price integrated by companies into their economic model. The explicit or implicit determinants of the carbon price include institutional decision, energy price and weather influence, as well as macroeconomic and financial shocks \cite{chevallier2013carbon}. A large and sudden increase in the carbon price, as assumed within the ECB's short-term CST scenario or in the NGFS scenarios, is plausible and may have important implications for banks \cite{chevallier2013carbon}.

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{Climate transition risk} refers to the financial risks that may arise from the transition to a low-carbon economy. These can stem from potential impacts of policies, regulations, significant investments, technological changes and consequently the financial performance and creditworthiness of economic activities \cite{masson2022global}. For example, policies aimed at reducing GHG emissions, such as carbon taxes or ETS, may increase the cost of carbon-intensive activities, and decrease the value of carbon-intensive assets. Similarly, advances in renewable energy technologies, may render fossil fuel assets stranded and lead to significant write-downs. As governments and companies worldwide take steps to reduce GHG emissions and shift towards a more sustainable business models, there are likely going to be significant impacts to the financial system. 
Banks are exposed to climate transition risks, as they provide financing and investment services to industries and companies that may be impacted by this shift. This can result in significant write-downs and losses for carbon-intensive companies, leading to increased credit risk and non-performing loans for banks. Banks that fail to address the climate transition risk may also face reputational damage, leading to a loss of customers and market share. Regulatory risk for banks may also increase as governments address climate change such as through increased capital requirements for carbon-intensive investments. However, opportunities may also arise for banks that are able to manage climate transition risk effectively, such as financing for renewable energy projects and green bonds.

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{Transition risk climate stress testing (CST)} is a type of stress testing that focuses on assessing the financial risks and resilience of institutions and systems to the transition towards a low-carbon economy. Transition risk CST involves the development of a range of scenarios that reflect different pathways to a low-carbon economy. These scenarios may include different levels of policy ambition, technological progress, socio-economic trajectories, market preferences and climate-related assumptions (e.g., global temperature rise and its impacts, carbon price, etc.). The aim is to assess the potential impact of these scenarios on financial performance, creditworthiness, and the resilience of the entity being tested. For example, the NGFS transition scenarios \cite{ngfs2021scenarios} are a set of four plausible pathways that describe how the global economy could transition to a low-carbon future: disorderly transition, delayed transition, orderly transition and chaotic transition. Each scenario is generated along with a carbon price trajectory. As in standard macro-financial regulatory stress tests, banks are required to stress their TMs with the scenarios \cite{schuermann2014stress}, and in particular with the additional costs related to the climate transition of the economy \cite{ecb2021climate}. 


\section{Key elements of our approach}
\label{sec:key_elements}

We want to assess the sensitivity of rating  transition matrices (TMs), to direct climate transition costs paid by companies (e.g., costs related to the carbon price). To do so, we need a function that relates factors that can be stressed with climate transition costs, to TMs. Moreover, the heterogeneity of sector vulnerability to climate transition costs requires a sectoral decomposition of risk. We decompose our approach into four key elements that are presented in the following subsections. 

\subsection{A factorial representation of rating transition matrices}
\label{sec:factor_represetation_tm}

A rating TM is a table that shows at what rate the credit ratings of entities (such as companies, countries, or financial instruments) have changed over time. %The TM typically shows the starting rating of an entity and the rating it has been assigned at a later point in time. The table can be used to track changes in credit quality and to analyze trends in credit risk. 
TMs contain lot of information about the creditworthiness of the counterparts of debt creditors, and their credit stability over time. For a rating scale containing $K$ plots ($K-1$ performing ratings, and one default rating), a TM lives into $[0,1]^{(K-1)\times K}$, hence in a relatively high-dimensional space. The reduction of TMs into low-dimensional generative factors that can be related to transition costs first requires the definition of a model that respects the TM's main features: positive entries and rows summing to $1$. 

\vspace{0.3cm}


In \cite{morgan1997creditmetrics}, the authors propose a one-parameter representation of TMs, used in several stress test models (e.g., \cite{schuermann2014stress,garnier2021climate}). It consists of two main steps. First, they transform the TMs into matrix $L$ as follows:

\begin{align}
\label{eq:TM}
    TM^{i,j}=\Phi(L^{i,j})-\Phi(L^{i,j+1}) \Longleftrightarrow L^{i,j}=\Phi^{-1}\left(\sum_{k=K}^j{TM^{i,k}}\right) 
\end{align}

\noindent where $\Phi$ is the cumulative distribution function of the standard Gaussian distribution, $TM^{i,j}$ is the transition rate from rating $r_i$ to rating $r_j$. Hence $L^{i,j}$ represents a threshold under which the rated asset jumps from rating $r_i$ to a rating in $\llbracket r_j, r_K \rrbracket$, with $r_K$ the last (default) rating. We must be careful with condition at limits (clipping the probabilities to avoid infinite factor values in $L$), as done in \cite{engelmann2021simple}. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Then, using a multi-factor Merton-Vasicek with general correlation matrix as in \cite{li2000default}, the log asset value $X^{(b)}$ of a borrower $b$ is determined by both systemic (macro-financial) factors $Z$ and an idiosyncratic factor $\epsilon$ such that 

\begin{align}
    X^{(b)}=a^T.Z+\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}\epsilon^{(b)}
\label{eq:multi_merton}
\end{align}

\noindent where $\epsilon^{(b)}$ and $Z$ are independent. $a \in \mathbb{R}^{n_f}$ are the factor loadings, $\Sigma \in [-1,1]^{n_f\times n_f}$ is the correlation between risk factors. 

Finally, we assume that a borrower with rating $r_i$ migrates to rating in $\llbracket r_j, r_K \rrbracket$ if $X^{(b)} \leq L^{i,j}$, i.e.:

\begin{align}
    \epsilon^{(b)} \leq \frac{L^{i,j} - a^T.Z}{\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}}
    \label{eq:epsilon_migration}
\end{align}

Since Merton-Vasicek assumes that the idiosyncratic risk is standard Gaussian, by mixing equations \eqref{eq:TM} and \eqref{eq:epsilon_migration} we obtain a model to generate TMs from factors $Z$ defined as:

\begin{align}
    TM^{i,j}(Z;L) = \begin{cases} 1 - \Phi(\frac{L^{i,2} - a^T.Z}{\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}}) \text{ if } j=1\\ 
                                \Phi \left(\frac{L^{i,j} - a^T.Z}{\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}}\right) - \Phi \left(\frac{L^{i,j+1} - a^T.Z}{\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}}\right) \text{ if }j \in \llbracket 2, K-1 \rrbracket \\
                                \Phi \left(\frac{L^{i,K} - a^T.Z}{\sqrt{1-a^T.\Sigma.a}}\right) \text{ if } j=K
                                \end{cases}
\label{eq:conditional_TM}
\end{align}

We assume that we observe \textit{point-in-time} (PiT) TMs, denoted $TM^{PiT}_t$, for $t \in [0, T]$. From these historical TMs we can compute a long-term \textit{through-the-cycle} (TTC) transition matrix, denoted $TM^{TTC}$. TTC matrix is computed as the sum of all the historical transitions, rescaled to be a TM. TTC is supposed to represent a rating TM related to a mean position in the economic cycle. 
The details of the matrices are given in Section \ref{sec:data}. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

Using the one-parameter representation given above, we can represent the PiT transition matrices with factors $Z$ by solving the problem:

\begin{align}
    Z=\arg \min_{Z} \int_{t=0}^T {\left\| \left(TM^{PiT}_t-TM(Z_t;L^{TTC})\right) \right\|_F^2}
    \label{eq:shift_problem}
\end{align}

\noindent where $L^{TTC}$ is derived from $TM^{TTC}$ using equation \eqref{eq:TM}, and $\|.\|_F$ is the Frobenius norm. With a factor $Z^s_t$ computed for a scenario $s$ at time $t \geq T$, we can generate a TM denoted $TM^s_t$. 

\subsection{Leontief sectoral breakdown of the economy}
\label{sec:leontief}

We remind that we focus on corporate exposure of banks, hence emphasizing the stress born by companies, and consequently by banks in their corporate portfolios. Compared to traditional macro-financial stress tests, the CST requires a sectoral breakdown of risks due to the heterogeneity of sector vulnerability to climate transition costs.
We propose to use a standard framework to model this sectoral decomposition of the economy: the Leontief input-output (IO) model \cite{leontief1949structural}. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

Leontief's IO model is a mathematical model used to analyze the interdependence of different locations and/or sectors in an economy. For simplicity, we call \textit{sector} the couple \textit{location-sector}, and for a better readability, we present the results summed at GICS-1 sectoral level (see Section \ref{sec:data} for details). Suppose there are $n$ sectors in an economy, and we have a vector of outputs from each sector denoted by $X = (x_1, x_2, ..., x_n)$, sold at price $P=(p_1, \dots, p_n)$. Let A be the $n\times n$ matrix of input-output coefficients, where $a_{ij}$ represents the amount of input $i$ needed to produce one unit of output $j$. The Leontief input-output model can be expressed mathematically as in \cite{marangoni2000leontief}:
\begin{align}
    X = AX + Y \Longleftrightarrow P=A^T P + V
\label{eq:leontief_open}
\end{align}

\noindent where $Y$ is a vector of final demand for the goods and services and $V$ is the value-added (VA) produced by the $n$ sectors. %We remind that the VA equals the difference between an industryâ€™s gross output (consisting of sales or receipts and other operating income, commodity taxes, and inventory change) and the cost of its intermediate inputs (including energy, raw materials, semi-finished goods, and services that are purchased from all sources). 
The equation \eqref{eq:leontief_open} states that the total output of each sector, $X$, is equal to the sum of the inputs required to produce that output, $AX$, plus the final demand for that output, $Y$. It also states that prices are formed by the sum of the input prices, $A^T P$, plus the final value-added created by the industry. If we denote $x_{ij}$ the quantity sold by the sector $i$ to sector $j$, we can infer the entries of matrix $A$ as $A_{ij}=x_{ij}/x_j$. From \eqref{eq:leontief_open} we obtain:

\begin{align}
    X = BY \Longleftrightarrow P=B^T V
\label{eq:leontief_close}
\end{align}

\noindent where $B:=(I-A)^{-1}$ is called the \textit{Leontief inverse}. The entries $B_{ij}$ represent the impact of a change in final demand in the $j^{th}$ sector on the $i^{th}$ sector's production, or in final value-addedof the $i^{}th$ sector on the $j^{th}$ sector's unitary price. The model depicts inter-industry relationships within an economy, showing how output from one industrial sector may become an input to another industrial sector. 

\begin{remark}
In \cite{bartolucci2020inversion}, authors give an interpretation of Leontief inverse matrix $B$. First, they note that $B=(I-A)^{-1}=\sum_{k=0}^\infty A^k$. Hence, the Leontief inverse $B$ contains all the input-output cycles until infinity, hence fully taking into account the dynamical aspect of the input-output model. If demand $Y$ increases, the production needs to adapt at first degree, i.e., increase by $IY$. Then, to meet their production increase $IY$, sectors demand inputs from economy, hence demand $AY$ (a first tour of the economy). To meet this new demand, sectors need to produce $A^2Y$, and so on. This modeling phenomena is called a cascade sectoral network \cite{cahen2021capital}. 
\end{remark}

\vspace{0.3cm}

