\subsection{Diffusion of transition costs across the sectoral value chain}
\label{sec:transition_costs_leontief}

To have a sectoral breakdown of the effects of climate transition costs in the rating TMs, we use the Leontief framework as in \cite{gemechu2014economic,mardones2020economic,adenot2022cascading}. These papers are presented in Section \ref{sec:related_work}. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

The direct GHG intensities (see definition in Section \ref{sec:definitions}) of the economy, by sector (or couple location-sector), related to the production of VA, is denoted $G=(g_1, \dots, g_n)$ for the $n$ sectors. At sectoral-level, we do not know how the intensity will evolve on the different scenarios. Yet, we know from the NGFS trajectories (presented in Section \ref{sec:data}) that the global intensity of the economy will change over time, at a rate that depends on the scenario. We can approximate the evolution of GHG intensity for the $n$ sectors by assuming that they all evolve at an equal rate, which would also be the global rate. We note $c_t^s$ the global carbon intensity coefficient at time $t \geq T$ for scenario $s$, computed as the ratio of the starting point intensity (computed at time $T$) and the projected intensities computed from the GDP and GHG emissions trajectories. Hence the starting point coefficient $c_T^s$ is equal to $1$ for all scenarios and evolves according to the trajectories of the scenarios. The intensity coefficient trajectories are shown in Figure \ref{fig:intensity_coefs} in Section \ref{sec:data}. Using these coefficients, $G_t^s:=(c_t^s g_1, \dots, c_t^s g_n)$ is therefore a plausible sectoral intensity vector at time $t$ for scenario $s$. % than a constant intensity $G$ as assumed for example in \cite{adenot2022cascading}.

\begin{remark}
    We note that if we had sectoral trajectories, we could compute sectoral coefficients $c_t^s=(c_t^{(s,1)}, \dots, c_t^{(s,n)})$, such that $G_t^s:=(c_t^{(s,1)}, \dots, c_t^{(s,n)})$ would be an even more plausible intensity vector at time $t$ for scenario $s$.
\end{remark}

Hence, for a scenario $s$ at time $t$, using Leontief model we define the GHG intensities both produced and imported throughout the value chain as $M_t^s = B^T G_t^s$. This intensity then is composed of the direct emissions (scope 1), the indirect emissions from imported energy and heat (scope 2) and the upstream emissions from imported product demanded by the production process (scope 3 upstream). These three categories can be complemented with the direct emissions of final demand (e.g., direct emissions in households related to the usage of the production of each sector) (scope 3 downstream) \cite{hasegawa2015carbon}. Yet, the sectoral direct GHG intensity of final demand is more difficult to estimate and is not directly related to the production process, even if final demand is a necessary condition of production. Hence, we do limit our model to scope 1, scope 2 and scope 3 upstream. We note that if we have the appropriate data, we can compute one sectoral intensity vector per location of imported production. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

We apply a carbon tax per ton of emitted GHG, denoted $\tau_t^s$, and then $\eta_t^s=\tau_t^s M_t^s$, being the vector of sectoral carbon tax per unit of production. %We note that we can apply a specific rate for each sector, for example considering the carbon leakage tax reduction (directive 2019/708/UE), to reduce the effects of carbon tax. 
The tax $\eta_t^s$ applies on the full production (hence the full price). The new model becomes $P=(1+\eta_t^s)[A^T P+V]$, then:

\begin{align}
    P\left(\tau_t^s\right)=(I-A(\tau_t^s)^T )^{-1}V
\end{align}

\noindent where
\begin{align}
    A\left(\tau_t^s \right) = \begin{cases} a_{ij} \text{ if } i \neq j \\
    a_{ii} + \left(1-\frac{1}{1+\eta_{t,i}^s}\right)
    \end{cases}
\label{eq:A_carbon}
\end{align}

\noindent Hence $P\left(\tau_t^s \right)=B\left(\tau_t^s \right) V$, with $B\left(\tau_t^s\right):=\left( I - A\left(\tau_t^s \right)^T \right)^{-1}$. In \cite{mardones2020economic}, under the assumption that the monetary value of the final demand remains constant and that the price elasticity of demand of all sectors is constant, the carbon price affects the total consumption hence the production at rate

\begin{align}
    R_i(\tau_t^s):=\frac{x_i(\tau_t^s)}{x_i} = \gamma_i \frac{p_i}{p_i(\tau_t^s)}
\label{eq:production_price_ratio}
\end{align}

\noindent where $x_i\left(\tau_t^s\right)$ is the production of sector $i$ after the introduction of sectoral carbon taxes $\eta_t^s$, $\gamma_i$ is an elasticity price-production for sector $i$. This last parameter can be determined from \textit{pass-through} mechanisms \cite{bodnar2002pass}. We therefore obtain a variation of production for sectors with respect to carbon price. We denote $R_i(\tau_t^s)$ the production decrease ratio related to carbon price $\tau_t^s$. As in \cite{adenot2022cascading}, under the assumption that the earnings are generated by the production, which is a reasonable assumption, $1-R_i(\tau_t^s)$ is the decrease in earnings. 

\begin{remark}
    Without better approximation, we use constant unitary production-price elasticity is conservative $\gamma_i=1$. Production shocks may be reduced $\gamma_i<1$, for example using empirical elasticity functions. Hence, the results obtained are the very conservative, creating a upper bound on the effect of carbon price. % Moreover, we assume the supply-demand equilibrium \cite{gale1955law}, which in short-term after the introduction of the tax can be broken.
\end{remark}

Finally, under the assumption of constant EV-EBITDA ratio (EV standing for enterprise value) \cite{mauboussin2018does}, authors of \cite{adenot2022cascading} consider that the valuation of a company is proportional to its earnings, they apply the shock $R_i(\tau_t^s)$ on EV. Hence the impact of carbon price $\tau_t^s$ on sectoral stock market indices is $1-R_i(\tau_t^s)$. 

\subsection{Effects of transition costs on transition matrices}

In order to stress the rating transition matrices, we use the conditional transition matrix function $TM(Z_t;L^{TTC})$. As said above, the factors $Z$ can be related to macro-financial factors, using for example regression models or expert knowledge. We note $X^{MF}$ the macro-financial variables, observed at each time $t$ and model $Z$ as:

\begin{align}
    Z_t=\beta^T X_t^{MF} + \epsilon_t
\label{eq:regression}
\end{align}

\noindent where $\epsilon_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)$. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

$X^{MF}$ can be composed with macro-economic indicators (e.g., gross domestic product), sectoral production indicators (e.g., sectoral gross-value added), socioeconomic indicators (e.g., unemployment), and credit quality indicators (e.g., credit spreads). 
The choice of explanatory variables depends on two main drivers. First, the regression must be significant, both in terms of prediction quality (e.g., mean-squared error between prediction and ground truth), quality of the fit (e.g., the $R^2$ of the regression) or the p-values of the coefficients of the regression. Second, in our case the variables that explain the factors $Z$ must be sensitive to carbon cost.

\vspace{0.3cm}

For the corporate TMs, we find that equity prices significantly explain the behavior of the factor $Z$. We assess the variations of the TMs with respect to transition risk using stressed equity prices/EV, hence:

\begin{align}
X^{MF}_t=\left[\Delta^{\%}_t E, Z_{t-1}, 1 \right]^T
\label{eq:x_MF}
\end{align}

\noindent where $\Delta^{\%}_t$ is the \textit{percentage of variations} operator, $E$ is the equity price/EV. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Two assumptions are possible for the variations of the sectoral equity prices related to carbon price. In a conservative assumption, equity prices of sector $i$ vary of $1-R_i(\tau_t^s)$. Hence, we choose

\begin{align}
    X^{MF}(\tau_t^s)=\left[(1-R_i(\tau_t^s)), Z^s_{t-1}, 1 \right]^T.
\label{eq:x_MF_carbon}
\end{align}

\noindent From macro-financial projections $X^{MF}(\tau_t^s)$ we can generate factors $Z^s_{t}$ using equations \eqref{eq:regression} and $TM_t^s$ using equation \ref{eq:conditional_TM}, i.e.:

\begin{align}
    TM^s_t = TM(\beta^T X^{MF}(\tau_t^s);L^{TTC})
\label{eq:tm_scenario}
\end{align}

\vspace{0.3cm}

We now have all the elements to stress TMs with direct (and indirect) effect of carbon price at sectoral level taking into account the chain value of the economy. An overview of the full model is given in Figure \ref{fig:overview_method}. 


