To our knowledge, no existing paper brings together standard TM modeling and value chain tax diffusion, and by extension no author has proposed a focus on TMs forward-looking stress test with carbon price trajectories and value chain diffusion, using a modeling framework that meets the requirements of CST exercises. The closest related works are described in the next section.  


\section{Related work}
\label{sec:related_work}

A consistent view of academics, professionals, public sector regulators and policy economists is that transition risks related to new regulations are a top climate risk to businesses and investors over the coming years \cite{stroebel2021you}. In particular, the regulations, for example the NDCs, in which a carbon pricing scheme is implemented, has a direct impact on transition costs paid by companies, that may have a large influence on their performance and creditworthiness. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Several studies have examined empirically the impact of carbon pricing on financial performance and risk. For instance, \cite{oestreich2015carbon} investigated the effect of the ETS on German stock market returns. They showed that companies that received EU allowances were on average better than ones who didn't. This result confirms the conclusions of \cite{oberndorfer2009eu}, which proposed a similar study carried out on electricity companies in several European countries, and of \cite{scholtens2014carbon}, which analyzed the positive effects of the EU-ETS system on stock market returns in four industries responsible for a majority of EU GHG emissions. Other studies have shown the extent to which market prices have already incorporated carbon risks. For example \cite{andersson2016hedging} showed that as long as climate change mitigation politics are pending, the low-carbon index performs in line with the benchmark; once GHG emissions are priced, the low-carbon index should start to outperform the benchmark. \cite{gorgen2020carbon} developed a measure of carbon risk and observed two opposite effects: high-emission companies have higher average returns, but when firms become relatively browner their returns are lower. They also showed that carbon risk premium is insignificant, suggesting that investors may not require compensation for bearing carbon risk. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Yet, the stress test is a forward-looking exercise, where historical data may be used to calibrate models but impacts are drawn from scenarios and associated carbon price trajectories that cannot be observed in past data. Therefore, we believe that specific models should be developed. In a regulatory context (see Figure \ref{fig:timeline}), climate stress tests assess the credit risk borne by banks over scenarios, and subsequent additional provisions. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Recent papers have examined the impact of carbon price change on credit risk.
\cite{battiston2017climate} were the first to propose the use of climate
scenarios from Integrated Assessment Models (hence in a scenario-based foward-looking view) to carry out climate stress tests of financial institutions in the context of transition risk. Authors had an empirical approach in which they compute the absolute and relative exposure of each financial actor type to different sectors with several exposure to climate transition risk (e.g., fossil-fuel, utilities, energy-intensive, housing, transport, etc.). They found that direct and indirect exposures to climate-policy-relevant sectors represent a large portion of investors' equity portfolios, especially for investment and pension funds, and that the portion of banks' loan portfolios exposed to these sectors is comparable to capital of banks. Finally, they computed individual banks' \textit{value at risk}, under green and brown investment strategies. \cite{jung2021climate} introduce a measure called CRISK for systemic climate risk assessment, which is the expected capital shortfall of a financial institution in a climate stress scenario. It consists of three steps. First, measure of a climate risk factor using stranded asset portfolio returns as a proxy measure for transition risk. Second, estimate of a time-varying climate beta of financial institutions using a Dynamic Conditional Beta model. Third, computation of CRISK as a function of a given financial firm's size, leverage, and expected equity loss conditional on climate-related stress, based on the SRISK measure of \cite{brownlees2017srisk}. \cite{garnier2021climate} modelled the loss of a credit portfolio using the Merton-Vasicek model with correlated climate risk factors (as exposed in equation \eqref{eq:multi_merton}). They applied their model to climate trajectories, mixing macro-financial risk factors, transition risk factors and regional physical risk factors. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

A widely used model to integrate carbon price risk into credit risk is the use of the structural Merton's model \cite{merton1974pricing}. 
For example, a study by the United Nations Environment Programme Finance Initiative \cite{unepfi2018extending} used the structural Merton's model to estimate the PD (Probability of default) of a counterparty including a carbon price. The Merton model describes the value of a company as the price of a call option on its assets with an exercise price equal to the company's liabilities. With this model, we can estimate the probability that a firm's assets will no longer offset its liabilities, and by extension estimate its PD. \cite{capasso2020climate} showed that Merton's PD is negatively associated with the amount of carbon emissions of a company, as well as its carbon intensity. \cite{bouchet2020credit} analyzed the impact of variations in the carbon price at the sectoral level, for a variation in the carbon price of up to \$20 for short-term risks, and up to \$780 for long-term risks, using a methodology also used in \cite{belloni2022euro}. However, both papers have two practical limitations for banks. First, the assumptions of Merton's model are particularly restrictive: perfect frictionless markets, each firm's liabilities are zero-coupon bonds, the value of the firm does not depend on its financial structure, and is a stochastic process with constant volatility. Second, the authors use only Scope 1 GHG emissions, which is not in line with the ECB's CST requirements. \cite{reinders2023finance} also used a structural Merton's model to assess the impact of a carbon tax shock on the market value of equity and debt instrument. As in \cite{bouchet2020credit} they assumed an instantaneous shock on asset value, but based on a ratio ``carbon cost on the net present value of the company" and not on a ratio ``carbon cost on EBITDA''. They apply their approach on the value of corporate debt and residential mortgages, in the Dutch banking sector. They find declines in the market value of banks' assets of 2â€“13\% of core capital for a â‚¬100 carbon tax shock, increasing to 6â€“29\% for a â‚¬200 carbon tax shock. Other authors use structural models to build endogenous credit risk default models. \cite{agliardi2021pricing} developed a bond pricing model, where jumps in firm's value are conditioned to both financial roots (e.g., earnings) and uncertainty about firm's carbon risk. They apply their model to firms issuing green bonds. \cite{le2022corporate} developed a structural model where the transition risk impacts' magnitude depends on an initially unknown transition scenario. This is progressively revealed through the observation
of the carbon price trajectory. The carbon price is assumed inflationary and modeled as a compound Poisson distribution (i.e., the adjustments of the carbon price are assumed i.i.d.). Depending on the scenario, the intensity of the involved Poisson distribution increases. The scenario probabilities are updated with the carbon price process, and consequently the firm's value and default probability. In \cite{battiston2022structural}, they went further and adjusted the credit risk not only with instantaneous carbon effects, but with the potential realisation of the transition scenarios, taking into account the dynamic evolution of firms' technological and financial structure.

\vspace{0.3cm}

A more practical approach was proposed by \cite{pineau2022sensibilite}, where authors presented a method for assessing the sensitivity of PDs to the carbon price by directly shifting financial variables of a rating calculator (based on financial ratios) with carbon cost (computed on the three scopes of carbon). The mean variations of PD confirmed and extended the results of \cite{bouchet2020credit}, by showing that Material, Utilities, Consumer Staples and Energy are the most sensitive to carbon price, with a variation of PD of 4-6\% for a carbon price increase of \$100 per ton equivalent. A similar example is the Axylia's Carbon Score\footnote{https://www.axylia.com/score-carbone-axylia}, which tells investors and individuals whether a company is \textit{creditworthy} and \textit{responsible} after subtracting from its revenues the cost of the carbon emitted. For banks, this Carbon Score is an indicator of the creditworthiness of the companies in their portfolios with regard to climate issues. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

Yet none of the previous contributions model the interdependence between sectors, with a diffusion of risks. To do so, several papers use the Leontief IO model and related IODs to incorporate environmental aspects in the typical input-output economic framework. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

In a seminal paper \cite{leontief1970environmental}, authors analyzed the pollution generated as by-product of economic activities. It considers two economic sectors taking into account the production of good and bad outputs (pollution) and includes a third sector: a pollution abatement sector. The inputs assigned to the latter are used to remove the pollution generated by the other two sectors. \cite{leontief1973national} proposed a linkage between IO tables with data on natural resource inputs, the transformation of the resources in the production process and the assessment of the formation of residuals resulting from the economic activity. They take into account the environmental negative impact coming from the economic activities through the assessment  of pollutants. They use an IOD that do not only include the intersectoral flows of goods and services but also the generation of pollutants and activities aimed at their elimination. \cite{steenge1978environmental} analyzes an apparent inconsistency in Leontiefâ€˜s formulation when including tolerated pollutants levels and proposed a reformulation of the model to bypass this problem. A non-negative vector of gross output levels for any final demand was guaranteed if  tolerated pollution exceeded total generated pollution.

\vspace{0.3cm}

Some papers directly model the diffusion of a carbon tax costs in the value chain of the economy, using Leontief framework. %In particular, \cite{gemechu2014economic} computes a sectoral tax rate, \cite{mardones2020economic} shows the variation of the sectoral production related to carbon tax and \cite{adenot2022cascading} models the variation of the valuation of companies after the introduction of the tax. 
\cite{gemechu2014economic} studied the direct and indirect effects when applying a $CO_2$ tax  on  Spanish products and services. They used an extended IO (EIO) model to estimate the sectoral $CO_2$ emissions intensities taking into account all the interactions between sectors and an environmental tax is set proportional to each sector's emissions intensity. Then a Leontief price model was used to investigate the impact of the environmental tax on the Spanish economy. This study enables us to analyze the trade-off between the economy, society and the environment, when applying an environmental tax. For instance, they showed that a tax on electricity production and distribution sector would imply a reduction of 2\% in the total $C0_2$ emissions. However it would lead to a negative impact on social welfare. 
\cite{mardones2020economic} studied the effect of global ($CO_2$) and local ($S0_2$, $NO_x$ and PM) air pollutants taxes in the Chilean economy as the result of the implementation of this policy after 2017. In general, an increase on the carbon tax rate leads to an increase of sectoral prices, implying a reduction of production. The energy sector is the most impacted with the application of the $C0_2$ tax. If the value of production is assumed to be constant in the short-term, the production of the Chilean electricity sector decreases by around 22.56\% when a carbon tax of 50 USD per ton of  $C0_2$ is applied. 
In \cite{adenot2022cascading}, an IO framework is used to estimate the impact of carbon price  at a firm level. Authors studied the cross-sector diffusion of the carbon cost through the value chain. They showed that the impact of carbon price is shared not only among high carbon-intensive sectors but also among low carbon-intensive sectors, due to the cascade effect on firm's supply chains. In particular, they demonstrated that when applying a carbon price of 50 USD, the earnings shocks suffered by the firms in low carbon-intensive sectors (Information Technology, Consumer Discretionary and Consumer Staples earning shows are around 3\%-4\%) are not negligible, with respect to the high carbon-intensive ones (Utilities, Energy and Materials earnings shocks are between 7\% and 12\%). 
Finally, \cite{cahen2021capital} remarked that production and consumption of fossil fuels should decrease drastically in order to achieve a low-carbon transition. However, the entire economic system could be affected by this process due to production network linkages. The authors proposed a method to assess how this defossilisation process could strand capital stocks across different countries and productive sectors. Their methodology is based on a multi-regional IOD (MRIO) and a supply-side model. They analyze stranding multipliers, which measure the exposure to the risk of becoming stranded. The fossil sector exhibits the highest external stranding multiplier. In addition, they found that sectors that are not affected by direct stranding links (as for instance public administration, real estate and land transportation) are highly exposed to indirect cascading effects. When analyzing external marginal stranding multipliers across countries, they found out that France, Australia and Slovakia are the ones with the highest values.

