\noindent \textbf{NGFS scenarios.} We use five scenarios for which economic and climate trajectories are jointly generated. These scenarios are projected trajectories proposed by the NGFS, generated by coupling climate-related assumptions and macroeconomic models of the National Institute Global Econometric Model (NiGEM)\footnote{\url{https://www.niesr.ac.uk/nigem-macroeconomic-model}}. The five scenarios are:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Below 2Â°C (B2)} scenario assumes a rapid and ambitious global transition towards a low-carbon economy, with significant investments in renewable energy, energy efficiency, carbon capture and storage, giving a 67\% chance of limiting global warming to below 2Â°C.
    \item \textbf{Net Zero 2050 (NZ50)} scenario is an ambitious scenario that limits global warming to 1.5Â°C through stringent climate policies and innovation, reaching net zero carbon emissions around 2050. This is with some jurisdictions such as the US, EU and Japan reaching net zero for all GHGs by this point.
    \item \textbf{Delayed transition (DT)} scenario assumes that policy and investment decisions are delayed, and that the pace of technological innovation is slower than anticipated, leading to a more gradual shift away from fossil fuels. Annual emissions do not decrease until 2030, resulting in the need for strong policies to limit warming to below 2Â°C.
    \item \textbf{Divergent Net Zero (DNZ)} scenario assumes that economies reach net-zero by 2050 but with higher costs due to divergent policies introduced across sectors and a quicker phase out of fossil fuels.
    \item \textbf{Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs)} includes all pledged policies even if not yet implemented
    \item \textbf{Current policies (CP)} scenario assumes that only currently implemented policies are preserved, leading to few transition risks but high physical risks.
\end{itemize}

