\noindent \textbf{Input-Output databases} (IOD) are databases that store information about the inputs and outputs of economic activities within an economy. It is a powerful tool for analyzing the interrelationships between different sectors of an economy and for estimating the impact of changes in one sector on the rest of the economy.

In an IOD, each sector of the economy is represented as a row, and each column represents a different sector. The entries in the database show the amount of inputs that each sector uses from other sectors, as well as the amount of outputs that each sector produces and sells to other sectors. IODs can be used for a wide range of applications, including economic analysis, environmental analysis, trade analysis, and policy analysis. Several IODs exist and are used in academic papers to model geo-sectoral interdependence. \textit{The World Input-Output Database (WIOD)}\footnote{\url{https://www.rug.nl/ggdc/valuechain/wiod/?lang=en}} is a multi-region input-output (IO) model, which captures the complex interdependence between 40 different countries whose economy is divided into 56 NACE sectors. \textit{EXIOBASE}\footnote{https://www.exiobase.eu/} is a global, detailed, and fully integrated environmentally extended multi-regional IOD that provides information on the environmental impacts of economic activities.  %It includes data on economic transactions between different sectors and regions, as well as information on the environmental impacts of these transactions.
It covers over 43 countries, and includes data on 163 industries and 200 products.  %EXIOBASE also provides information on a wide range of environmental impacts, including GHG emissions, air pollution, water use, and land use. 
\textit{The Full International and Global Accounts for Research in input-Output analysis (FIGARO)\footnote{\url{https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/esa-supply-use-input-tables/data/database}}} is an IOD of EU Member States and 18 main EU trading partners, with annual inter-country IO tables product by product and industry by industry (with NACE classification). \noindent \textit{The OECD Inter-Country Input-Output (OECD-ICIO)}\footnote{\url{https://www.oecd.org/sti/ind/inter-country-input-output-tables.htm}} contain detailed information on the flows of goods and services between industries and between countries, and the inputs required to produce these goods and services. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

For the experimental part of our paper, we use the FIGARO database since it gathers all the requirements for our problem (NACE sector classification like ECB regulatory exercises, and data that goes up to 2020). 

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{GHG emissions data.} The FIGARO database also provides GHG emissions data, for the same countries and industries as the IODs presented above. Hence, from the FIGARO database we gather geo-sectoral production and geo-sectoral GHG emissions, and estimate geo-sectoral GHG intensities (i.e., the vector $G$). % (see Table \ref{tab:intensities}).  %Users can search and download data, create custom tables and charts, and access the latest news and publications. The database includes data on topics such as national accounts, trade, employment, education, health, and the environment.

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{Historical macro-financial variables.} For the illustration, we use the historical annual growth rate of S\&P500 index for the period of 2001-2018 to fit our model, and the related TMs and macro-financial environment, before introducing carbon prices trajectories given in the NGFS scenarios. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

