\section{Direct effect of carbon price on US transition matrices}
\label{sec:experiments}

In this section, we apply our model to US data in order to illustrate the full end-to-end integration of carbon price shock into corporate TMs, to assess the exposure of bank's coporate portfolios to direct carbon price risk. We note that the model demonstrated in Section \ref{sec:key_elements} is fully implementable with free data and open source language. The code to reproduce will be released after publication. 

\vspace{0.1cm}

We take $T=2018$ (last point of observed historical PiT TMs. Hence $T+1=2019$ is the starting point of all scenarios. 

\vspace{0.3cm}

\noindent \textbf{Factor inference and relation with macro-financial variables.} We first extract the factor $Z$ using equation \eqref{eq:shift_problem}, shown in Figure \ref{fig:shifts_prediction} (orange line). Second we fit the parameters of the regression \eqref{eq:regression} on historical S\&P500 index growth, to explain historical factor $Z$ with macro-financial variables. Factor and prediction are displayed in Figure \ref{fig:shifts_prediction} and Table \ref{tab:regression_shift}. We therefore have a model to generate US TMs with equity price growth. 

