\section{Conclusion}

 In our paper, we proposed a methodology to assess the effect of carbon price (paid by companies) on bankâ€™s rating corporate transition matrices. Such a methodology enables to compute the sensitivity of bank's to carbon price through the creditworthiness of their corporate portfolios. Our approach is based on three main elements of credit risk management and economic modeling. First, we used a one-parameter representation of transition matrices to obtain a generative factor and a model, from which we can generate new transition matrices. Second, we related this factor to equity growth such that we can generate transition matrices in relation with the macro-financial environment. Third, we used a sectoral decomposition of the economy using an input-output framework called Leontief model. Using this model, we can diffuse a carbon cost across the value chain of the economy, at geo-sectoral level. We plugged this third model to the equity growth involved in the generation of transition matrices. We finally obtained an end-to-end model to stress transition matrices using carbon costs, taking into account the dependence structure of the economy throughout the sectoral value chain. We have illustrated the effect of NGFS scenarios on the transition matrices of the US economy on ten macro-sectors (GICS classification). We observe the diffusion of the risk in the upper triangular part of the transition matrices, and by extension in the estimated probabilities of default. With such a tool, banks, who manage their regulatory capital, using transition matrices, can introduce the direct effect of transition costs into their credit risk management. They can thereby answer regulatory exercises involving climate transition risks. We note that our model can be generalized to any additional cost associated with climate change mitigation, such as energy prices.  

